 succeeded in 0ms:
     1	# Perf regression detection (0.7.2 PR-7)
     2	
     3	**Status:** landed (0.7.2 PR-7). Owns `dev/perf-history/` + the
     4	`perf-regression-check` binary (`fathomdb-cli` crate, layout (A) — a
     5	`[[bin]]` entry, NOT a new workspace crate).
     6	
     7	## Purpose
     8	
     9	Persist canonical-CI / release-time performance numbers per commit and
    10	surface regressions automatically with a deliberately **low false-positive
    11	rate**. The store is the ship-verdict history; the bin reads it, groups by
    12	`(ac_id, n)`, and compares the single most-recent run in each group against
    13	the rolling median of the prior runs in that group.
    14	
    15	## Append-only invariant
    16	
    17	`dev/perf-history/` is **append-only**. The `perf-regression-check` binary
    18	**only reads** the directory — it never writes, mutates, or deletes any
    19	file. New rows are written by CI (or by a human at release time, for the
    20	locally-measured AC-013 / AC-013b / AC-019 numbers). This keeps the history
    21	a tamper-evident, git-tracked audit trail: a regression is a new file whose
    22	numbers the bin flags, not an edit to an old file.
    23	
    24	## Record schema
    25	
    26	One JSON file per canonical run (filename convention:
    27	`<ac_id>-<commit_sha:8>-<n>.json`, e.g. `AC-013-c893d8b0-10000.json`). The
    28	bin globs `*.json` in the directory and parses each file as one record:
    29	
    30	```json
    31	{
    32	  "commit_sha": "c893d8b0",
    33	  "ac_id": "AC-013",
    34	  "n": 10000,
    35	  "p50_ms": 36.0,
    36	  "p99_ms": 49.0,
    37	  "recall": 0.937,
    38	  "timestamp": "2026-06-01T07:23:39Z"
    39	}
    40	```
    41	
    42	| field        | type            | required | notes |
    43	|--------------|-----------------|----------|-------|
    44	| `commit_sha` | string          | yes      | commit the run was measured at |
    45	| `ac_id`      | string          | yes      | `AC-012` \| `AC-013` \| `AC-013b` \| `AC-019` \| … |
    46	| `n`          | integer         | yes      | corpus row count; part of the grouping key |
    47	| `p50_ms`     | number          | no\*     | median latency; omit for recall-only ACs |
    48	| `p99_ms`     | number          | no\*     | tail latency; omit for recall-only ACs |
    49	| `recall`     | number \| null  | no       | recall@10; omit/null for latency-only ACs (AC-012, AC-019) |
    50	| `timestamp`  | RFC3339 string  | yes      | run time; used to pick the single latest run per group |
    51	
    52	\* A record must carry at least one comparable metric (a latency pair or a
    53	recall value), else it is malformed.
    54	
    55	**Forward-extensibility:** unknown fields are **ignored, not rejected**.
    56	Adding fields to the schema later does not break older readers or invalidate
    57	older files. (`serde` with default `deny_unknown_fields` OFF.)
    58	
    59	## Grouping — tier-aware
    60	
    61	Records are grouped by the **`(ac_id, n)`** pair. This is deliberate:
    62	
    63	- AC-013 @ N=10k is never compared against AC-013 @ N=100k (different
    64	  latency tier — see `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised.md`, the
    65	  10k binding tier vs the 100k/1M tracked tiers).
    66	- The real-corpus anchor (N=7667) is a **different group** from the
    67	  synthetic N=10000 run — real bge and synthetic isotropic data have
    68	  different absolute numbers and must not cross-contaminate a median.
    69	
    70	**Regime caveat (grouping is necessary but not sufficient).** `(ac_id, n)`
    71	does not capture every comparability axis. The K-sweep that landed in 0.7.1
    72	(top-K bit-candidates 64 → 192, the EU-7/PR-2 recall fix) raised rerank cost,
    73	so pre-0.7.1 (K=64) latency is **not** directly comparable to 0.7.1+ (K=192)
    74	latency even at the same `(ac_id, n)`. The committed store therefore does
    75	**not** mix K=64 and K=192 latency in one group — the synthetic AC-013 @
    76	N=10000 latency history begins at the K=192 PR-3 baseline (`c893d8b`). The
    77	K=64-era synthetic recall arc (AC-013b @ N=10000) is kept as one
    78	internally-consistent group because every point in it is K=64. When a future
    79	regime change (a new K, an ANN index) lands, start a fresh comparison rather
    80	than letting the detector flag the deliberate step as a regression.
    81	
    82	## Detection thresholds (HITL Gate 1 — LOCKED 2026-06-01)
    83	
    84	Per HITL sign-off on 2026-06-01, the thresholds are:
    85	
    86	| metric  | flag condition                                            |
    87	|---------|-----------------------------------------------------------|
    88	| latency | `p50` **or** `p99` degraded **> 15%** vs the rolling median |
    89	| recall  | recall degraded **> 0.03 absolute** vs the rolling median   |
    90	| window  | rolling median of the prior **up to 10** runs per group     |
    91	| latest  | the **single most-recent** run (by timestamp) per group     |
    92	
    93	**Rationale (false-positive resistance is the design priority — codex's
    94	review focus):**
    95	
    96	- Recall σ = **0.0116** (PR-3 measured, N=7667 anchor;
    97	  `0.7.2-PR-3-perf-data.md`). A **0.03** absolute threshold is ≈ **2.4σ**,
    98	  i.e. roughly a **~1% jitter false-flag rate** — the deliberate
    99	  low-cry-wolf choice. We would rather miss a marginal real drift than fire
   100	  on noise, because a fired flag costs human triage on every canonical run.
   101	- **Tradeoff acknowledged:** a 0.03 recall drop from the 0.937 anchor lands
   102	  at **0.907**, which is right above the **0.90** floor. So this threshold
   103	  favours **false-positive resistance over early-warning sensitivity**: a
   104	  recall decay that creeps toward the floor in <0.03 steps will not trip the
   105	  detector before it nears 0.90. That is an accepted limitation; the hard
   106	  recall floor is enforced separately by the AC-013b gate, not by this
   107	  drift detector.
   108	- **15% latency** allows for normal run-to-run variance on shared CI
   109	  hardware (the canonical runner is a 4-core EPYC slice; cold-cache and
   110	  neighbour-noise swing latency more than recall).
   111	
   112	The "latest = single most-recent run vs the median of the prior runs in the
   113	window" definition means a one-off bad run flags immediately (good for catch
   114	latency) but a single good run after a bad streak does not mask the streak
   115	(the median is robust to one outlier).
   116	
   117	## Insufficient history
   118	
   119	A group with **fewer than 2 runs** (i.e. no prior runs to form a median
   120	after removing the latest) is reported as **insufficient-history** — NOT a
   121	regression and NOT a crash. The AC-012 @ N=1M group is exactly this case
   122	today (one documented canonical run, v0.6.1 `603a4bc`).
   123	
   124	## Timestamp parsing
   125	
   126	`timestamp` is parsed as **strict RFC3339** (`YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS(.frac)?(Z|±HH:MM)`)
   127	to UTC epoch seconds at load time, and the **parsed epoch** — not the raw
   128	string — is the ordering key for "latest run". A lexical string sort would
   129	silently mis-order offset-bearing or differently-formatted timestamps and
   130	thus pick the wrong "latest" run; instead, a timestamp that does not parse is
   131	a **data-integrity failure (exit 2)**, surfaced loudly rather than tolerated.
   132	The parser is dependency-free (the workspace pulls in no date crate); see
   133	`parse_rfc3339_epoch` + its unit tests in the bin source. Ties on the same
   134	instant break deterministically on `commit_sha`.
   135	
   136	## Exit codes
   137	
   138	| code | meaning |
   139	|------|---------|
   140	| `0`  | no regression flagged (includes all-insufficient-history) |
   141	| `1`  | at least one group flagged a regression |
   142	| `2`  | data missing or malformed (directory absent, unreadable JSON, record with no comparable metric, **or an unparseable timestamp**) |
   143	
   144	## Output
   145	
   146	- Default: human-readable report to stdout (one block per group; flagged
   147	  groups marked clearly).
   148	- `--json`: machine-parseable JSON object to stdout (per-group verdicts +
   149	  an overall `flagged` boolean), for CI and tooling to consume.
   150	
   151	## CI integration (`.github/workflows/perf-canonical.yml`)
   152	
   153	After the AC-012 canonical run, the workflow builds and runs
   154	`perf-regression-check dev/perf-history/`, echoes the report to the step log,
   155	and writes it to **`$GITHUB_STEP_SUMMARY`**.
   156	
   157	- **Channel choice:** this workflow is **`workflow_dispatch`-only**, so there
   158	  is no `pull_request`/`push` event to comment on — a PR-comment step would be
   159	  dead code on every real run, and `pull-requests: write` would be an unused
   160	  permission over-grant. The step summary is the `workflow_dispatch`-safe
   161	  surface, always present, and visible on the run page. The workflow keeps
   162	  only `contents: read`.
   163	- Exit **1** (regression flagged): the step **continues** — the summary is
   164	  the signal, not a hard failure. (A regression on a diagnostic dispatch run
   165	  should not red-X the run; a human reads the summary.)
   166	- Exit **2** (data integrity): the step **fails loudly** (`::error::` + non-zero
   167	  exit) — malformed history is a real defect in the store and must block.
   168	
   169	The workflow stays `workflow_dispatch`-only (no push/PR/schedule triggers
   170	added) and keeps within GitHub's workflow_dispatch input cap (≤ 8 inputs, per
   171	the prior consolidation fix).
   172	
   173	## Backfill provenance
   174	
   175	The committed `dev/perf-history/` rows are backfilled from:
   176	
   177	- **AC-012 @ N=1M** — v0.6.1 canonical CI run `603a4bc` (run 26346417896,
   178	  2026-05-23): p50=140.95, p99=458, verdict RED (over the 20/150 ADR
   179	  budget). Source: `dev/notes/perf-canonical-runner-2026-MM.md`. **This is
   180	  the only documented AC-012 canonical run → its group is sparse
   181	  (insufficient history).** It is an honestly-RED historical point, not a
   182	  regression the detector should flag (no prior to compare against).
   183	- **AC-013b synthetic @ N=10000** — the 2026-05-27 PERF-VECTOR-QUANT recall
   184	  arc (K=64 throughout), the full four-point sequence:
   185	  - `035cfa3` (the buggy parent of the fix): recall **1.0** — **DEGENERATE**.
   186	    The batch-collapse left ~10 distinct vec0 rows per 10K writes, so the
   187	    brute-force ground truth and production both returned the same
   188	    trivially-small set, making recall *falsely perfect*
   189	    (`STATUS-perf-vector-quant.md:138`). This is a **measurement artifact, not
   190	    a verdict** (so marked in the row's `note`).
   191	  - `4a95cfd` (the fix) + scanner fix `53a270d`: recall **0.1572** — the
   192	    *honest* number once the collapse was repaired. Low not because of the
   193	    bug but because `VaryingEmbedder` produces sparse vectors (6/768 non-zero)
   194	    — a synthetic-fixture pathology (`:143`).
   195	  - `38f5e3a` (Option-1 dense fixture): recall **0.5124**.
   196	  - `38d5f4f` (v0.7.0 ship): recall **0.5124** — AC-013b NOT MET on the
   197	    synthetic fixture (deferred to 0.7.1 EMBEDDER-UNDEFER).
   198	- **AC-013 / AC-013b / AC-019 real bge @ N=7667** and **AC-013 synthetic @
   199	  N=10000 (K=192)** forward baseline — v0.7.1 / 0.7.2 (`c893d8b`, 2026-06-01) +
   200	  PR-3 local data. Source: `dev/plans/runs/0.7.2-PR-3-perf-data.md`. AC-013
   201	  rows are latency-only; AC-013b rows are recall-only (the two ACs measure
   202	  different things).
   203	
   204	### Honesty note — what the batch-collapse bug actually did, and what this detector can and cannot catch
   205	
   206	The handoff success criterion says the bin should "flag the 2026-05-27
   207	batch-collapse bug." Tracing the real numbers (`STATUS-perf-vector-quant.md`)
   208	shows the premise needs correcting, and we record the truth rather than
   209	contorting the data to fit it:
   210	
   211	**The batch-collapse bug masqueraded as an *improvement*, not a regression.**
   212	With the index collapsed to ~10 rows, recall read a *false* 1.0 and latency
   213	was *anomalously fast* (the bit-KNN searched a ~10-row partition instead of
   214	10K). A degradation-only detector — flag recall *drops* and latency *rises*,
   215	which is exactly what HITL locked — **structurally cannot flag that bug**;
   216	the bug's signature is the opposite of a degradation. What the detector *does*
   217	catch is the **regression-shaped correction** that follows: when `4a95cfd`
   218	repaired the collapse, recall fell from the degenerate 1.0 to the honest
   219	0.1572 — a 0.84 drop the detector flags (the `backfill-dirty` fixture proves
   220	this; the flagged commit is the *fix*, `4a95cfd`, which is counter-intuitive
   221	but honest). The committed store keeps the full arc; its latest run per group
   222	(v0.7.0, 0.5124) is healthy, so the committed store itself is **clean**.
   223	
   224	Catching the *bug itself* would require a different check — a row-count /
   225	vec0-population invariant, or an "implausible perfection" anomaly rule (recall
   226	== 1.0 exactly, or latency falling as N rises). That is **deliberately out of
   227	scope** for this degradation detector (it would expand past the HITL-locked
   228	15%/0.03 thresholds and risk false positives on legitimately-perfect small-N
   229	recall) and is logged here as **future work**.
   230	
   231	**The v0.6.1 AC-012 @ N=1M run was a real RED verdict** (7× over the p50
   232	budget) — preserved faithfully in the store, not smoothed away. It does not
   233	flag as a *regression* only because it is the sole point in its group
   234	(insufficient history); its RED-ness is a separate budget fact recorded in
   235	`perf-canonical-runner-2026-MM.md`.
   236	
   237	**Sparse history is the honest current state.** Because of the regime changes
   238	above (K=64 → K=192, synthetic → real bge) and the once-per-release cadence,
   239	most `(ac_id, n)` groups today hold a single comparable point and report
   240	*insufficient-history*. The only group with a real multi-point comparison is
   241	the K=64 AC-013b @ N=10000 arc. The store accrues comparability as new
   242	canonical runs are appended on a stable regime; the detector is wired and
   243	correct now, and gets more sensitive as history deepens.

