     1	# `dev/perf-history/` — append-only canonical perf history
     2	
     3	One JSON file per canonical / release-time performance run. The
     4	`perf-regression-check` binary (`fathomdb-cli` crate) reads this directory,
     5	groups records by `(ac_id, n)`, and flags regressions of the most-recent run
     6	in each group against the rolling median of the prior runs.
     7	
     8	**This directory is append-only.** The bin only ever *reads* it; CI (or a
     9	human, for the locally-measured AC-013/AC-013b/AC-019 numbers) *writes* new
    10	files. Never edit or delete an existing row — a regression is a new file
    11	whose numbers the bin flags, not a mutation of history.
    12	
    13	Filename convention: `<ac_id>-<commit_sha:8>-<n>.json`
    14	(e.g. `AC-013-c893d8b0-10000.json`).
    15	
    16	Schema, thresholds, and provenance: `dev/design/perf-regression-detection.md`.
    17	
    18	```json
    19	{
    20	  "commit_sha": "c893d8b0",
    21	  "ac_id": "AC-013",
    22	  "n": 10000,
    23	  "p50_ms": 36.0,
    24	  "p99_ms": 49.0,
    25	  "recall": 0.937,
    26	  "timestamp": "2026-06-01T07:23:39Z"
    27	}
    28	```
    29	
    30	Unknown fields are ignored (forward-extensible) — e.g. the optional `note`
    31	field used to annotate provenance / artifacts is not interpreted by the bin.
    32	`recall` is omitted/null for latency-only ACs (AC-012, AC-019);
    33	`p50_ms`/`p99_ms` are omitted for recall-only ACs (AC-013b). `timestamp` must
    34	be strict RFC3339 — an unparseable one is a data-integrity failure (exit 2),
    35	because the parsed instant (not the raw string) selects the latest run.
    36	
    37	The 2026-05-27 `AC-013b` arc records a known artifact: the batch-collapse bug
